Language Barrier: 
While the medical universities in Russia teach the MBBS program entirely in the English language, there are still a majority of people who speak Russian. So, the universities offer international students with language classes as part of their curriculum so that they can navigate through daily life in Russia smoothly, communicate with locals and travel around without any hindrance. Thus, leading a great life as an Indian student in Russia. 

Food and Dietary Habits: 
Indian students may find the taste of Russian cuisine bland and tasteless as it is hearty and meat-based and not spicy and flavourful like most of the Indian dishes that the students are used to. Some Indian students are also vegetarian so it is difficult for them to adjust to the new dietary habits in Russia. Hence, some of the leading medical universities in Russia provide facilities of Indian mess making life as an Indian student in Russia more comfortable. 

Climate Differences: 
India is a country that experiences typically warm and tropical climates but witnesses almost all four seasons throughout the year- summer, winter, fall, and rainy. On the other hand, Russia experiences cold and snowy winters and warm summers that are still cool towards the Arctic coast. Hence, life as an Indian student in Russia belonging to the Southern region and some parts of Central India may find it difficult to adjust to the cold and chilling weather. 

Social Customs and Etiquette: 
Indian culture is known for stressing the sense of belongingness and respect for elders while Russian culture values individualism and self-expression. Life as an Indian students in Russia who come from a background where they’re dependent on their parents and had constant support and guidance from elders are sure to find it difficult to cope with the new social construct of Russia.  
